@ricotz th efix for this issue actually causes a lot of issues for things that were working perfectly fine before and are also perfectly fine Vala (it just can't make use of fast-vapi anymore).

The example in this issue was actually invalid Vala anyways and this is the main reason why fast-vapi was generating invalid code. As fast-vapi does no symbol resolution and thus no type checking or whatsoever, it fails to detect that this is actually invalid Vala. However, this is an intended feature of fast-vapi.

There actually exists an example which is valid Vala and triggers a similar bug, and there also already is a work around for const outside classes for it, but not for consts in classes:

```vala
public class Foo {
    private const string test2 = "Test";
    public const string test = test2;
}
namespace Bar {
    private const string test2 = "Test";
    public const string test = test2;
}
```

Is valid Vala and fast-vapi 0.46.3 translates it to
```vala
/* foo.vapi generated by valac 0.46.3, do not modify. */
using GLib;
[Source (filename = "foo.vala", line = 5, column = 1)]
namespace Bar {
	[Source (filename = "foo.vala", line = 6, column = 5)]
	internal const string test2 = "Test";
	[Source (filename = "foo.vala", line = 7, column = 5)]
	public const string test = test2;
}
[Source (filename = "foo.vala", line = 1, column = 1)]
public class Foo {
	[Source (filename = "foo.vala", line = 3, column = 5)]
	public const string test = test2;
	[Source (filename = "foo.vala", line = 1, column = 1)]
	public Foo ();
}
```

You can see that in the `namespace Bar` the `private const test2` was changed to `internal const test2` keeping the `public const test` valid. The `private const text` in `class Foo` was removed as described in the original issue.

With valac 0.46.4 the following happens:
```vala
/* foo.vapi generated by valac 0.46.4, do not modify. */
using GLib;
[Source (filename = "foo.vala", line = 5, column = 1)]
namespace Bar {
	[Source (filename = "foo.vala", line = 6, column = 5)]
	internal const string test2 = "Test";
	[Source (filename = "foo.vala", line = 7, column = 5)]
	public const string test;
}
[Source (filename = "foo.vala", line = 1, column = 1)]
public class Foo {
	[Source (filename = "foo.vala", line = 3, column = 5)]
	public const string test;
	[Source (filename = "foo.vala", line = 1, column = 1)]
	public Foo ();
}
```

Which isn't really an improvement, because now both cases are invalid with the error `A const field requires a value to be provided` when `--use-fast-vapi` flag is provided (if that flag is not set the error message becomes `External constants cannot use values` for the `internal const test2`.

tl;dr this change is build breaking for some projects that use fast-vapi in their build process and it was applied to various versions...

